    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "He then quotes V. W. Turner, The Forest of\nSymbols (1967), 44, who states that \u201c. . . at their deepest level rituals reveal values\nwhich are sociological facts.\u201d\nIntroduction\n33 New York: Doubleday & Company, 1964.\n34 Comparison and contrast could here be made with the Babylonian perspective in\nthe creation epic titled \u201cEnuma Elish\u201d (for which see A. Heidel, The Babylonian\nGenesis [Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1942]).\n35 W. Brueggemann, Theology of the Old Testament (Minneapolis: Fortress Press,\n1997), 191.\n36 An Anno Mundi (lit., \u201cyear of the world,\u201d i.e., since creation) calendar is still used\nin Judaism.\n37 See A. Jepsen, \u201cZur Chronologie des Priesterkodex,\u201d ZAW 47 (1929): 251-55.\n38 In the biblical world, counting (with decimal-place notation) was done both in\nbase-ten (as in our modern system) and in base-sixty.\n39 W. Brueggemann, Theology of the Old Testament, 191.\n40 This connection is forcibly made by M. Douglas, Leviticus as Literature, 132.\n41 E.g., 20:26; cf. 10:10; 11:44-45; 19:2; 20:7.\n42 This crucial point is excellently discussed by J. Milgrom, Leviticus 1\u201316, 42-45.\n43 J. Milgrom, Leviticus 1\u201316, 43.\n44 The procedure is outlined at length in L. Bailey, Biblical Perspectives on Death\n(Philadelphia: Fortress Press, 1979), 28-32.\n45 M. Douglas, Leviticus as Literature, 4.\n46 That this was rationale for the gradation in sacrificial offering was recognized and\nexplicitly stated by the rabbis. That Israel\u2019s cult was not unique in this regard is\nattested from Mesopotamian literature wherein grain is explicitly described as the\noffering of the economically stressed. For explicit citations, see J. Milgrom, Leviticus",
    "Unknown": "They make a stir about external rights, observation of days and meats, but to the power of religion and godliness are strangers, and experience nothing of a divine change on their souls.",
